sentence: Welcome to Seeking Alpha's Stocks to Watch - a preview of key events scheduled for the next week.
Follow this account and turn the e-mail alert on to receive this article in your inbox every Saturday morning.
While investors can expect a continuation of the political dance between Washington D.C. and Pyongyang, the question is are investors tuned into the distraction?
"The reality of the situation is starting to dawn on markets that this is political theater engineered for domestic consumption.
The reality is it doesn't change the economic outlook at all," noted CMC Markets analyst Michael McCarthy.
There's also no avoiding some trade talk this week with the temporary tariff exclusion for European Union nations, Mexico and Canada on steel and aluminum due to expire on June 1.

Some analysts believe the trade negotiations could end up a zero-sum game where certain industries benefit at the expense of others, meaning the trick for investors will be to end up on the right side of the trade ledger when the winners and losers are sorted out.
There is some red meat for investors to chew on this week, with the private payroll report and U.S. GDP numbers due out on May 30 followed by China's official monthly manufacturing index on May 31.
The economic headliner of the week will be the May jobs report on June 1.
Expectations are for jobs adds of 164K and an unemployment rate of 3.9%.
Wages are expected to go up at a moderate pace (+0.1% M/M, +2.6% Y/Y).
Crude oil prices will also be in the spotlight after a 4% tumble on Friday.

Notable earnings reports: Salesforce.com ( CRM ), VMware ( VMW ) and Hewlett-Packard ( HPQ ) on May 29; Michael Kors ( KORS ), Dick's Sporting Goods ( DKS ) and Box (BOX) on May 30; Lululemon (LULU), Costco (COST), GameStop (GME) and Dollar Tree (DLTR) on May 31; Abercombie & Fitch (ANF) and Hovnanian Enterprises (HOV) on June 1.
See Seeking Alpha's Earnings Calendar for the complete list.
IPO lockup expirations: Reto Eco-Solutions (RETO) and Boxlight (BOXL) on May 29.

Analyst quiet period expirations: Carbon Black (CBLK), PermRock Royalty Trust (PRT), Inspire Medical Systems (INSP), Unity Biotechnology (UBX), Spirit of Texas Bancshares (STXB), Construction Partners (ROAD) and Aslan Pharmaceuticals (ASLN) on May 29.
Starbucks: The coffee chain will close about 8K stores for racial bias training on the afternoon May 29.
While the closing is a fairly high-profile event, most analysts expect very little impact for Starbucks on sales and profit from the publicity.
A bigger issue for the company is said to be the challenge of boosting sales during the afternoon daypart with comparable sales growth during the morning hours seen as maxed out at many locations.
Shares of Starbucks (SBUX) are down 9% over the last 52 weeks.
Projected dividend hike announcements: Deere (DE) to $0.67 from $0.60, Lowe's (LOW) to $0.49 from $0.41, El Paso Electric (EE) to $0.37 from $0.335, W.R. Berkley (WRB) to $0.15 from $0.14.

Notable Analyst/investor meetings: CA (CA) on May 30; LKQ (LKQ), Public Service Enterprise Group (PEG), Tetra Technologies (TTI), Luxoft (LXFT) and Molina Healthcare (MOH) on May 31, Tivity Health (TVTY) on June 1.
FDA watch: A decision is expected from the agency on TherapeuticsMD's (TXMD) Yuvvexy TX-004HR vaginal drug product candidate.
Bernstein Strategic Decisions CEO Conference: A screaming roster of CEOs will be in the Waldorf-Astoria in New York City from May 30 to June 1 to talk strategy.

The list of speakers includes the bosses from Clorox (CLX), McDonald's (MCD), MCormick & Company (MKC), Sysco (SYY), Citizens Financial Group (CFG), Capital One Financial (COF), Discoer Financial (DFS), Goldman Sachs (GS), Intercontinental Exchange (ICE), M&T Bank (MTB), Synchrony Financial (SYF), Wells Fargo (WFC), Bank of America (BAC), Blackstone (BX), Mastercard (MA), SunTrust Banks (STI), Mondelez International (MDLZ), Tupperware (TUP), Home Depot (HD), HAsbro (HAS), Texas Instruments (TXN), Kimberly-Clark (KMB), F5 Netowrks (FFIV), Sabre (SABR), Applied Materials (AMAT), Cadence Design Systems (CDNS), Cognex (CGNX), Cognizant Technology (CTSH), Citrix Systems (CTXS), Juniper Networks (JNPR), Boeing (BA), Intel (INTC), Pfizer (PFE), Las Vegas Sands (LVS), Visa (V) and Micron (MU).
What to do with Chevron and Exxon Mobil?
: Schaeffers Research warns that Chevron (CVX) could endure a third weekly loss next week if history repeats.
The research firm notes that over the past 10 years CVX has been one of the worst stocks to own during Memorial Day week.
Something has to give with the 10-day call/put volume ratio of 4.09 ranking in the 98th percentile of the annual range.
Schaeffers is also pointing to Exxon Mobile (XOM) as a historic Memorial Day week laggard, noting the energy stock ends the holiday week lower or flat about 90% of the time.
Crypto watch: Regulatory concerns are still lingering over cryptocurrencies.
Over the last seven days, Bitcoin (BTC-USD) isdown 9.0%, Ethereum (ETH-USD) isdown 14.3%, Litecoin (LTC-USD)fell 11.0% and Ripple (XRP-USD)dropped 8.7%.
Bucking the broad downtrend is TRON (TRON-USD), which isup 5% over the last week.
M&A watch: The La Quinta (LQ)-Wyndham Worldwide (WYN) deal is expected to close on May 30.
The walk date on the Talos Energy (TALO)-Stone Energy deal is May 31.
It's probably a safe bet that there will be some more NXP Semiconductos (NXPI)-Qualcomm (QCOM) news to digest once again.
Action in Bentonville and Seattle: As part of Walmart's (WMT) annual shareholder meeting the company has a formal business and shareholders meeting scheduled for May 30.
The retailer will also host an associate meeting on June 1 with a presentation by execs and a Q&A session with the investment community.
All three will be streamed live .
Amazon (AMZN) will hold its annual shareholder meeting in Seattle on May 30.
U.S. auto sales: Edmunds expects U.S. auto sales to increase 3.5% Y/Y in April to 1.565M units.
The research firm sees an estimated seasonally adjusted annual rate of 16.7M for the month.

"Despite rising gas prices, shoppers are clearly demonstrating their confidence in the strength of the economy as they continue to seek out larger, more expensive vehicles," notes Edmunds analyst Jeremy Acevedo.

May forecast by automaker - General Motors (GM) +13% to 268K, Ford (F) -2% to 225K, Toyota (TM) -1% to 217K, Fiat Chrysler (FCAU) +9% to 210K, Honda (HMC) +3% to 152K, Nissan (NSANY) -9% to 125K, Hyundai/Kia (HYMLF) flat at 119K, Volkswagen (VLKAY) +9% to 52K.
Tesla: Tesla (TSLA) will pause production at the Fremont factory between May 26 and May 31 to work on the assembly line.
GBH Insights' Daniel Ives thinks Model 3 production has ramped up to a 3K-3.5K a week pace after an Everest-like uphill battle.
Ives expects the magical 5K/week Model 3 production pace to arrive in the early part of July.
Nevada casinos: The Nevada Gaming Control Board will post revenue numbers for April by the end of the week.
The last report saw Las Vegas Strip casinos post a 9% increase for March, although on a fiscal YTD basis Strip gaming win is up only 1%.
An even bigger development for Las Vegas casinos is the potential strike of 50K casino and hotel workers spread across 30 resorts.
It's unclear what the impact on tourism would be even if the strike is short, but MGM Resorts (MGM) and Caesars Entertainment (CZR) have the most exposure.
Macau: An update on gross gaming revenue for May could arrive from regulators as early as June 1.
Analysts expect another stellar month, with estimate ranging from +15% to +20%.

Casino stocks that could move after the numbers are released include Wynn Macau ([[WYNMF]], [[WYNMY]], [[WYNN]]), Sands China ([[SCHYY]], [[SCHYF]], [[LVS]]), MGM China ([[MCHVF]], [[MCHVY]], [[MGM]]), Galaxy Entertainment (GXYEF), SJM Holdings ([[SJMHF]], [[SJMHY]]) and Melco Resorts & Entertainment (MLCO).
Box Office: Disney's (DIS) Solo: A Star Wars Story is tracking to open in a range of $130M to $150M for the long holiday weekend, although early tracking indicates a shortfall.
The global haul for the Lucasfilm production is expected to top $300M for the weekend.
Barron's mentions: The publication names the world's best CEOs in its cover story.
New additions to the 2018 list include Best Buy's (BBY) Hubert Joly, Red Hat's (RHT) James Whitehurst, Electronic Arts' (EA) Andrew Wilson and Marriott International's (MAR) Arne Sorensen.
Notable scratches from last year's list include Anheuser-Busch InBev's (BUD) Carlos Brito and Comcast's (CMCSA) Brian Roberts.
As for stocks, Altice USA (ATUS) is called a winning bet and the low valuation on Micron (MU) is analyzed in detail.
